    "reasoning": {
      "overall": "Mexico host the 2026 World Cup opener at Estadio Azteca as clear favourites (FIFA rank ~15 vs South Africa's 60), backed by a refurbished Azteca, altitude, and a vocal home crowd. El Tri are unbeaten in five matches in 2026 (3W-2D, +6 GD) including credible draws with Portugal (0-0) and Belgium (1-1), but since the 2025 Gold Cup Mexico has scored only four goals in seven FIFA-window games, getting blanked four times. A heavy injury list — Malagón (Achilles, out), Edson Álvarez (ankle surgery, late-April return), Gilberto Mora (pubalgia), plus Marcel Ruiz, Luis Chávez, Huescas, Araujo and Huerta — limits attacking variety. South Africa are well-organised under Hugo Broos with a favoured 4-3-2-1/4-3-3 with a consistent backline, captain Ronwen Williams in goal and Burnley's Lyle Foster up top, but of the eight African nations that qualified by topping their group, South Africa scored the fewest goals and conceded the most, and they recently went 1-1 and lost 1-2 to Panama. The H2H is iconic but skinny: they last met in the 2010 opener, a 1-1 draw with South Africa as host. Market consensus matches: Dimers gives Mexico 64.7%, draw 21.5%, South Africa 13.9%; bookmakers price Mexico around 1.5. Expect a cagey, low-event opener with Mexico edging it via territorial control and set-pieces rather than a thrashing.",
